[[File:Gandhala- mother & child 28-6-04.jpg|thumb|right|180 px|Bodh mother and child near [[Gandhola Monastery]]]]
The '''Bodh people''', also known as '''Bhot''',{{sfn|Bhasin|Singh|Walter|Bhardwaj|1983|p=16}} are an ethnic group of [[Himachal Pradesh]], India. They are found in [[Lahaul tehsil]], [[Lahaul and Spiti district]],{{sfn|Singh|Bhasin|Singh|2008|p=193}} predominantly in the [[Bhaga valley|Bhaga]] and [[Chandra valley]]s, but also to a lesser extent in [[Pattani valley]],{{sfn|Bhasin|Singh|Walter|Bhardwaj|1983|p=16}} Miyar Valley, in the upper reaches of [[Pangi, Himachal Pradesh]] and [[Paddar]] valley, [[Jammu and Kashmir]].  Their religion is predominantly [[Buddhism]].{{sfn|Bhasin|Singh|Walter|Bhardwaj|1983|p=16}}
<!--"Bodhs converse with one another in their mother tongue Lahauli dialect or Pattani dialect" (Bhasin 1983:16). not sure which one this is.-->

==Art & Craft in Himachal==
The art and craft of any region is a reflection of its environment,people and traditions. This statement is apt for Negi and Bodh tribes of Himachal Pradesh,which borrows elements from its scenic surroundings to create “pahari” jewellery,breathing a sense of rigour and sturdiness.

While some communities have unique traditions, some ornaments are common to all. These include neck ornaments are common to all. These include neck ornaments like hansli or small pendants called toke and the most cherished necklaces called the coin necklaces.

